Mike Clark wrote:

&gt; 
&gt; On Nov 20, 2003, at 3:02 PM, Lasitha Ranatunga wrote:
&gt; 
&gt;  &gt; I&#39;ve been solving this kind of duplication by creating my own
&gt;  &gt; assertions.
&gt;  &gt; As an example, see my version of CalculateAgeTest below.  I&#39;m curious
&gt;  &gt; about
&gt;  &gt; the pros/cons of each approach?
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; cheers, lasitha.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; ----------------
&gt;  &gt; package ca.bluejays.scouting.amateur.model.test;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; import java.util.Date;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; import junit.framework.*;
&gt;  &gt; import XXX.BiographicalReport;
&gt;  &gt; import XXX.PlayerFactory;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; import com.diasparsoftware.java.util.DateUtil;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; public class CalculateAgeTest2 extends TestCase {
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;     public void testBirthday() {
&gt;  &gt;         assertCorrectAge(30, DateUtil.makeDate(2004, 5, 4));
&gt;  &gt;     }
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;     public void testDayBeforeBirthday() {
&gt;  &gt;         assertCorrectAge(29, DateUtil.makeDate(2004, 5, 3));
&gt;  &gt;     }
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;     public void testDayAfterBirthday() {
&gt;  &gt;         assertCorrectAge(30, DateUtil.makeDate(2004, 5, 5));
&gt;  &gt;     }
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;     public void testDateOfBirth() {
&gt;  &gt;         assertCorrectAge(0, DateUtil.makeDate(1974, 5, 4));
&gt;  &gt;     }
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;     public void testInvalidFutureDate() {
&gt;  &gt;         assertCorrectAge(0, DateUtil.makeDate(1974, 5, 3));
&gt;  &gt;     }
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;     private void assertCorrectAge(int expectedAge, Date futureDate) {
&gt;  &gt;         BiographicalReport biographicalReport = PlayerFactory
&gt;  &gt;                 .makeBiographicalReport(&quot;Joe&quot;, &quot;Rainsberger&quot;, DateUtil
&gt;  &gt;                     .makeDate(1974, 5, 4));
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;         assertEquals(new Integer(expectedAge),
&gt;  &gt;                      biographicalReport.getAgeAsOf(futureDate));
&gt;  &gt;     }
&gt;  &gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; To my mind, this approach is more explicit than the parameterized test
&gt; case example.  That is, I prefer the level of test language used here
&gt; over the language used to coerce JUnit to do it for me.  But that&#39;s
&gt; just my mind...

Agreed: it&#39;s easier to understand, but more tests mean more code. I 
wanted to be able to write tests with data. Why duplicate all that stuff?!

I don&#39;t think overriding runTest() and creating a TestSuite &quot;by hand&quot; is 
so advanced: it&#39;s how JUnit worked before they added the 
reflection-based stuff, anyway. Go back and re-read Test Infected: their 
first example is the groundwork for a Parameterized Test Case! 
(Hand-built suite() and override runTest().)
